# Simple Key-Value Store

A key-value database with a command-line interface. Built from scratch for
CSCE 4350. Supports strings, hashes, lists, counters, key expiry, range
queries, and transactions. Data survives a restart.

**Author:** Roman — EUID `rms0465`

## Design

### The hash table is my own

The project doesn't let you use Python's built-in `dict`, so `hashtable.py`
is a hash table I wrote. A key is hashed to a bucket index. Two keys can
land in the same bucket, so each bucket holds a small list of `[key, value]`
pairs that gets searched one by one. The table doubles in size once it's
75% full, which keeps those lists short.

Setting a key that already exists overwrites it. That's what gives you
last-write-wins.

A hash's fields are stored in another HashTable, so I reuse the same class
at both levels.

### Persistence: an append-only log

Every write gets appended to `data.db` as one line of JSON:

```
["SET", "user:1", "alice"]
["EXPIRE", "user:1", 1751900000.0]
["FLUSHDB"]
```

Nothing already in the file is ever changed. Only added. So if the program
dies mid-write, the worst that happens is the last line is garbage, and
everything before it is fine. A broken line gets skipped on load.

On startup I read the file top to bottom and re-apply every record. Since
they're applied in order and the newest write wins, I end up in exactly the
state I was in before.

Two things I had to get right:

- **EXPIRE logs the deadline, not the duration.** If I logged "expires in
  60s" and replayed the log a day later, the key would get a fresh 60
  seconds. So I log *when* it dies.
- **INCR logs a SET with the result.** I record what the value became, not
  that an increment happened. Replay never has to do math, so it can't
  disagree with what actually happened.

Records are JSON arrays, not objects, so the file format doesn't depend on
a map type either.

### Expiry is checked on read, not on a timer

There's no background thread cleaning up dead keys. Each key stores its
deadline, and every read goes through `_live()`, which checks the clock and
deletes the key if it's past due. Nothing else can see a dead key because
nothing else reads keys directly.

### Transactions: snapshot + buffer

`BEGIN` copies the whole store and starts holding log records in memory
instead of writing them. `COMMIT` writes them out. `ABORT` puts the copy
back and throws the records away.

Both parts matter. The copy has to be a *deep* copy, or changes made during
the transaction would also change the copy and there'd be nothing to roll
back to. And the log writes have to be held back, or an aborted
transaction's changes would already be on disk and replay would bring them
back.

Writes hit memory right away, so you can read your own changes inside a
transaction.

## Files

```
main.py           the command loop, parsing, and dispatch
hashtable.py      the hash table used as the index
store.py          values: string, hash, or list, plus optional expiry
persistence.py    the append-only log
tests/            unit tests and black-box CLI tests
.github/workflows/ci.yml   runs flake8 + pytest on every push
```

## Running

```bash
python3 main.py
```

Type one command per line. It also reads piped input, which is how the
automated tester drives it:

```bash
printf 'SET greeting hello\nGET greeting\nEXIT\n' | python3 main.py
```

Data goes in `data.db`, which is git-ignored since it's runtime data, not
source.

## Commands

| Command | Result |
|---|---|
| `SET <key> <value>` | `OK` |
| `GET <key>` | the value, or an empty line if missing |
| `DEL <key>` | `1` if removed, `0` if it wasn't there |
| `EXISTS <key>` | `1` / `0` |
| `MSET <k> <v> ...` | `OK` |
| `MGET <k> ...` | one line per key |
| `INCR` / `DECR <key>` | the new number |
| `EXPIRE <key> <ms>` | `1` / `0` — TTL is in **milliseconds** |
| `TTL <key>` | ms left, `-1` (no expiry), `-2` (no key) |
| `RANGE <start> <end>` | matching keys sorted, then `END` |
| `HSET <key> <field> <value>` | `1` |
| `HGET <key> <field>` | the value, or empty |
| `HGETALL <key>` | `field value` per line, then `END` |
| `LPUSH` / `RPUSH <key> <value>` | the list's new length |
| `LPOP` / `RPOP <key>` | the element removed |
| `LRANGE <key> <start> <stop>` | elements, then `END`; `-1` means last |
| `BEGIN` / `COMMIT` / `ABORT` | `OK` |
| `FLUSHDB` | `OK` |
| `EXIT` | quits |

RANGE bounds are inclusive. An empty bound (`""`) means no limit on that
side. Using the wrong command for a type (like `LPUSH` on a string) returns
`ERR wrong type` instead of wrecking the value.

## Testing

```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
flake8 .
pytest -q
```

- `tests/test_hashtable.py` — the hash table on its own, including two keys
  colliding into the same bucket.
- `tests/test_store.py` — the value types, including that `clone()` really
  is a deep copy, since transaction rollback depends on it.
- `tests/test_cli.py` — runs the actual program as a subprocess and pipes
  commands in, including restarting it to check that data persisted and that
  an aborted transaction stayed aborted.

GitHub Actions runs flake8 and the tests on every push.